>>114563849
The loudness you get depends on how much bandwith each element in your mix uses. In the case of your example, its a extremely barebones track with really nothing in the mids and highs so sonny can just smash that shit into a clipper really hard without it starting to pump or distort.

You would not get this sort of loudness with a very lush and rich sounding track without it sounding distorted in parts or without lowend or highend ducking.

In your case, you should start lowcutting and highcutting instruments. Like sub bass that doesnt need alot of top end and leads and instruments that doesnt need low end.

Also learn to use a clipper.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114563849
use two limiters. It'll let you get more volume while staying fairly transparent, compared to if you tried getting that same volume with one limiter

>>114563849
Listen here, I'll tell you how to compete in the loudness war. Go to each individual sound in your track and analyse it with an oscilloscope. If you see peaks in the waveform get rid of them with a clipper or limiter, but listen carefully to not overdo it. As soon as the sound changes back off, we don't want to change the sound only get rid of those little peaks. Do this also on your bus channels and on the master channel, before the compressors in the signal chain. You probably have to bounce those tracks due to the amount of clippers/limiters needed to give your CPU some relief. If you bounce those tracks remember to use the highest oversampling option.

If done correctly you'll have so much more headroom on the master channel with almost no audible difference in sound, your compressors will work more smoothly without those peaks and with your last limiter you'd be able to push hard for loudness. See pic and compare the numbers in the red boxes.

I was wondering the following, which, perhaps someone here can provide an answer.

Let's say an album has 9 songs (all the same genre, style, feel, etc.). In order for them to sound consistent and similar to one another, is it customary to mix one track and use that as the sort of "template" when mixing the rest? For example, saving EQ, reveb, etc. settings for a crash cymbal in one song and then just simply applying those same settings to the crash cymbal in the next song? And the same for snare, etc.? And then of course, could that same principle be applied to guitars, vocals, etc. etc. etc.?

pls /prod/, I'm this close to releasing

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114568171
No, each song should be mixed individually. Sound choice is probably more important than mixing. So you are making a conscious decision in the production to create a consistent and cohesive sound for an album. You limit yourself in terms of drum kits, drum machine, instruments, synths, mic...
You can of course copy some mixing tools for example using the same room reverb so it sounds like all tracks were recorded in the same room. Or using the same plugins with their specific characters like compressors, color EQ, saturation and so on. But the mixing process itself should be individual, don't limit yourself to a "template" of another song.

Mastering is something else. Here you are doing subtle changes and it is common to A/B test and use other songs of the album as a reference to create the final touches for a cohesive sound.

You could objectively check the intonation and action at different frets. You can see how well the frets were finished or check how straight the neck is. There should be no dead spots anywhere on the fretboard. The controls should be relatively clear of noise. You can also objectively compare your retail price to what it would cost you to order one on ebay or reverb.
If you're buying to learn all of this crap then just get the cheapest piece you can get your hands on. Everything will be shit, but you're going to go to Stewmac to get luthier tools and start correcting issues and upgrading parts.
If you're buying to learn how to play, then pick the one you can see yourself playing and feels pretty decent. Give yourself a highish budget because they won't lose much or any value being 2nd hand already.

>>114556032
>Though I also think that the theatrical/drama element plays a major role in the singing style of opera too.
True. Expression is just as important as beautiful singing in opera. Opera also developed parallell with the development of singing. The first time a tenor ever sang a full high C with 'chest' was in 1831. All music before that tenors had sung high Cs in a more falsetto-like voice. Opera has always had an element of bravura and virtuosity. But it gradually went from singing fast and high notes to all the more singing powerful and high notes, which suits the expressive, dramatic nature of the art form very well.

posts.com: And then it was Liszt’s turn at the piano, as Mendelssohn begged him to play something new and striking. Liszt, however, was determined to get his revenge and have some fun at Mendelssohn’s expense. “So I seated myself at the piano,” Liszt reports, “and announced that I would perform the Mendelssohn Capriccio, Op. 5, arranged for concert performance by myself. In a second the guests had comprehended that I intended to avenge Mendelssohn’s butchering of my poor Rhapsodic, although I suppose many thought it a rather hazardous attempt to play a difficult composition in a new garb or arrangement on the spur of the moment, especially with the composer sitting within two yards of the keyboard. However, I did what I had announced to do, and at the conclusion, Mendelssohn, instead of bursting out with indignation and rage at my impudence and liberty, took my right hand in his, and turned it over, backward and forward, and bent the fingers this way and that, finally remarking laughingly that since I had beaten him on the keyboard, the only way of vindication was to challenge me to a boxing match. However, since he had now examined my hand, he would have to abandon that particular course of action. So everything passed over smoothly, and what might have been a very unpleasant meeting turned out a most enjoyable evening.”

posts.com:
>>114584219
Because they used professional musicians and recorded the basic tracks with a lot more people playing at once.

I don't know specifically how Sunflower was recorded, but if you take Revolver vs Pet Sounds, most tracks on Revolver were built on initial group takes that were just a rhythm guitar, drums, maybe a second guitar, bass or piano, and then the rest was done with a few overdubs.

A track from Pet Sounds, in comparison, would just be a single take of a 20+ musician orchestra with drums, percussions, two or more bass instruments, brasses, guitars, keyboards etc, and the only overdub would typically be the vocals.

We're gotten really good at recording overdubs nowadays, but I guess at the time it often resulted in a pretty "dry" sound. For some instruments that might be desirable (Ringo's drum sound is still something people try to emulate nowadays, for instance), but if everything in the mix sounds as dry, not so much. If you take early Tame Impala for instance, the bass and drum sound pretty Beatles-like, but the guitars are heavily distorted and echoed in order to fill the sound. If you have those dry drums plus dry guitars, well, you get a Beatles song.

Recording like The Beach Boys did meant that you got a nice amount of natural reverb from the room they recorded in and the amount of instruments filled a lot of the spectrum (this is where the Spector influence comes in). Even productions with fewer instruments than Pet Sounds like Sunflower probably benefits heavily from the feel of several pro musicians being in the same room.

Plus The Beatles' sound relied much more on electric guitars, and guitar sounds were pretty crummy in the 1960's, before distortion and better amps became commonplace. That being said, Beatles mix do sound a bit better if you listen to them in mono - still not as good as the Beach Boys, but they make a bit more sense and feel less like they have empty space between the instruments than if you listen in stereo.

>All of those songs were recorded around the same time
Half were recorded in late 66 or early 67 while the other half were recorded in mid to late 67. The span is about a year.
>and didn't previously appear on any other albums
In America. But they appeared as singles in both America and the world and the first side was released as an EP, which was The Beatles' intention.
>A compilation album includes tracks recorded over a wide span of time that appeared on different albums
Not necessarily. Something like The Hit Parade by The Wedding Present is obviously a compilation album, and has a shorter time span being the tracks being recorded than Capitol's MMT.
>Why isn't the Magical Mystery Tour included?
Because it wasn't a studio album released by The Beatles. It was a compilation album assembled by their America label. It's like asking why Hey Jude or Yesterday and Today isn't there.
>>114580001

>while the Yellow Submarine, a literal compilation album, is considered a studio album?
Yellow Submarine was deliberately released by The Beatles and Apple as a Soundtrack to the movie. It's less cohesive as say, Help! or A Hard Day's Night, but it belongs to that family.

What do you prefer?
Enema of the State is by far their biggest album, while also being their ''poppiest/glossiest''
That doesn't make it bad at all though, the guitar sounds and drumming is great, not to mention Jerry Finn's production which makes the guitars crush and sing.
Cheshire Cat and Dude Ranch are more skate punk, if you like that start at the song ''Dammit''
After Enema they did Take Off Your Pants and Jacket, which the joke of that title goes over everyones head.
This is basically Enema part 2 but with a little more experimentation, I use that word lightly because it is still very poppy. But TOYPAJ has some of blinks best drumming, Travis is a machine. Not to mention Jerry Finn's production makes the whole thing eargasmic.
For reference, Jerry Finn produced blinks biggest albums and is often regarded as the 4th member of blink for turning their ideas/demos into great sounding songs.
Now, their magnum opus in my opinion, their 2003 self titled/untitled album.
This is peak blink for me, its not overly poppy but not overly hardcore/experimental.
They finally went in a new direction (partly thanks to Tom and Travis' side project Box Car Racer which is an absolute recommend)
The guitar and bass sound on this album is phenomenal and Travis' drumming is insane as usual.
They recorded a lot of the album in a house and used 50's microphones and stereos.
Not to mention they recorded multiple drum and vocal tracks across a giant room giving them a huge spacey effect.
It also features Robert Smith of The Cure. That song is amazing on its own, but its even better when you listen to the track before it as they fade into each other with the same riff.
It speaks for itself really, just listen.
My favourites off that album:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xsOxyakxN5Y
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GehHvgiNJ70
These are the 2 songs that fade into each other with the latter featuring Robert Smith https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ybor_QT2iYI
